      "solution": "#include <stdio.h>\n#include <string.h>\n#include <stdlib.h>\n\nstatic int sbox[256];\nstatic int preimg[256][256];\nstatic int preimg_cnt[256];\nstatic int cands[16][256];\n\nvoid buildPreimage(int W) {\n    int numLines = 256 / W;\n    memset(preimg_cnt, 0, sizeof(int) * numLines);\n    for (int x = 0; x < 256; x++) {\n        int line = sbox[x] / W;\n        preimg[line][preimg_cnt[line]] = x;\n        preimg_cnt[line]++;\n    }\n}\n\nint main() {\n    for (int i = 0; i < 256; i++)\n        scanf(\"%d\", &sbox[i]);\n\n    int W, K, N;\n    scanf(\"%d %d %d\", &W, &K, &N);\n\n    buildPreimage(W);\n\n    for (int i = 0; i < K; i++)\n        for (int j = 0; j < 256; j++)\n            cands[i][j] = 1;\n\n    char buf[4096];\n    int ch;\n    while ((ch = getchar()) != '\\n' && ch != EOF);\n\n    for (int obs = 0; obs < N; obs++) {\n        if (!fgets(buf, sizeof(buf), stdin)) break;\n\n        int pos, p;\n        int hits[32];\n        int nhits = 0;\n\n        char *tok = strtok(buf, \" \\t\\n\\r\");\n        pos = atoi(tok);\n        tok = strtok(NULL, \" \\t\\n\\r\");\n        p = atoi(tok);\n\n        while ((tok = strtok(NULL, \" \\t\\n\\r\")) != NULL) {\n            hits[nhits++] = atoi(tok);\n        }\n\n        int obs_cand[256];\n        memset(obs_cand, 0, sizeof(obs_cand));\n\n        for (int h = 0; h < nhits; h++) {\n            int L = hits[h];\n            for (int k = 0; k < preimg_cnt[L]; k++) {\n                int val = preimg[L][k] ^ p;\n                obs_cand[val] = 1;\n            }\n        }\n\n        for (int j = 0; j < 256; j++)\n            cands[pos][j] &= obs_cand[j];\n    }\n\n    for (int i = 0; i < K; i++) {\n        int found = -1;\n        for (int j = 0; j < 256; j++) {\n            if (cands[i][j]) { found = j; break; }\n        }\n        if (i > 0) printf(\" \");\n        printf(\"%02X\", found);\n    }\n    printf(\"\\n\");\n\n    return 0;\n}",
      "statement": "A classified encryption device performs lookups in a substitution table (S-box) during each encryption step. You discovered that these lookups leave traces in the CPU cache — a timing side-channel vulnerability known as a <<Flush+Reload attack>>.\n\n<<How the device works:>>\nThe S-box is a permutation of values {{0}} to {{255}}. For each byte of the secret key, the device computes an index: [[index]] = [[key_byte]] {{XOR}} [[P]], where [[P]] is the known plaintext byte (a decimal integer, {{0}}–{{255}}). It then reads {{SBOX}}[[[index]]]. This access loads one <<cache line>> into the CPU cache.\n\n<<Cache model:>>\nThe cache partitions the {{256}} possible <<output values>> into lines of width [[W]]. There are {{256}}/[[W]] lines, numbered from {{0}}. Line [[L]] covers output values from [[L]]×[[W]] to [[L]]×[[W]]+[[W]]−{{1}} inclusive. When the output {{SBOX}}[[[index]]] falls in line [[L]]'s range, that line is loaded.\n\n<<Example:>> With [[W]]={{64}}, the cache has {{4}} lines:\n• Line {{0}}: covers output values {{0}}–{{63}}\n• Line {{1}}: covers output values {{64}}–{{127}}\n• Line {{2}}: covers output values {{128}}–{{191}}\n• Line {{3}}: covers output values {{192}}–{{255}}\nSuppose [[index]]={{42}} and {{SBOX}}[{{42}}]={{100}}. Since {{100}} is in range [{{64}},{{127}}], cache line {{1}} is loaded.\n\n<<Your attack:>>\nBefore each observation, you flush the entire cache. The device encrypts a known plaintext byte [[P]] against one byte of the secret key. You then probe the cache and record which lines are loaded (<<HIT>>).\n\nIn a clean environment, exactly <<one>> cache line is loaded per observation. In noisy conditions, additional lines may also appear loaded due to other processes running on the same CPU.\n\n<<Your goal:>>\nRecover all [[K]] bytes of the secret key using the provided observations.",
